THIS HAD NEVER HAPPENED TO ME AT ANY RESTAURANT I HAD EVER VISITED!!!! Truly wonderful.. Exceptional service.  A second visit, and paella again, but to be honest, it could be a lot better.  The sofrito is bland and needs a re-think.  There is no sense of smoked paprika which should be in a good paella.  There is no color from saffron -- it only takes a tiny bit.  And, most disappointedly, there is no socarrat, the crunchy rice from the bottom of the pan.  This is a rice dish with either chicken or seafood, and it is served elegantly by a great staff.  But as paella, it is just wanting.

If you go to a spanish restaurant you'd expect the best paella.  It seems that doesn't happen here.The seafood paella was so disappointing!! Raw lobster and shrimps, the rice was so bad that we ended up taking the plate to go. I don't think any spanish cook made that paella. That would've been a sacrilege for my spanish grandparents. I ordered Paella de Langosta. I dont know whether this is because of covid making their business slow so they just wanted to get rid of old food or what but if I could give 0 stars for the review I would. I wanted to like the food but obviously the lobster was not fresh and I wasnt going to take any chance eating anything else in he box. The only thing eatable was the bread. The rice didnt look like yellow rice (not in person) it was greasy and mushy. In the pic it look yellow but it is not. The lobster was so mushy it crumbled in my hand when I tried to pull the tail out of the shell. The claw was so mushy it didnt come out in one piece. It just was not eatable. Eat at your own risk. They did however, give me my money back but I just had to let people know about this. I love paella but this was not a hit.

This restaurant has a lot going for it.  It’s location, which is close the White House; and it’s interior, which is sparkling red like you might find in a historic castle.  However, I did not leave elated.  I ordered the lunch menu for $30 which included a salad, main course and dessert.  The special lunch is a good value when you compare to menu items individually.  Thumbs up to the warm bread and salad.  The pork skewers and the flan dessert not so much.  All items were presented well and the dessert was too pretty to consume.  However, the pork was tough even to cut and it was drizzled with a less than inspiring gravy.  For such an upscale restaurant, I left feeling like it was not worth the cost.

Highly recommend planning an evening out here! To start with, the ambiance is classy, but comfortable and the staff are very friendly and attentive. We picked a couple of tapas to start with, the fried eggplant and honey being our favorite pick since it was delicious and something none of us had tried before.  For dinner we got the classic Fideua (seafood and vermicelli cooked like paella) which was also very good and plenty of food for the two of us that were splitting it.  Near 8 in the evening (Saturday) live music started so we stayed to enjoy that and split some dessert. The torrija with toffee was outstanding, melts in your mouth!  Food, wine, service, ambiance were all great! Put this at the top of your places to visit when you're looking for good Spanish food!

After trying Taberna Del Alabardero at a charity event years ago, I finally made it to the restaurant for happy hour. When you walk in, you see a fancy bar in front, lounge area to the right and dining room to the left. You have to be able to climb stairs to access the restrooms upstairs.  Happy Hour occurs Monday from 11:30am to 10pm and Tuesday to Friday from 3:00pm to 7:00pm in the bar and lounge area. The Happy Hour menu features food and drink specials.  I started my meal with a glass of Sangria Blanca, which was garnished with apples and orange. Despite skipping breakfast and lunch, I overestimated how much I could consume in one setting.  I ordered four tapas - Toasted Bread with Tomato and Garlic, Serrano Ham and Manchego Cheese, Truffled Mushroom Croquettes, and Fried Calamari. I liked everything except the croquettes because they were too rich, creamy, and heavy.  I plan to return to enjoy a sit down dinner some time in the near future.

Delightful. Tasty. Sumptuous. We chose the restaurant week menu. Three Tapas, Paella, and Deserts. Each dish proved to be a stand-alone delight. The bread at the start is exceptional. Then, the Gambas Al Alijo, simmering hot with the garlic, the patatas bravas well done(could have used a bit more sauce) and the peppers filled with goat cheese, to add a hint of sweetness. To top it -- the Paella Valenciana!! rabbit and chicken morsels tossed in with charred artichokes, blending the sauce and rice to satiate your senses. And then, triple desert in the form of a gelatinous tiramisu, a rice puddingish type confection, and the last one I can't remember as it went down in a gulp!!

Very authentic food from Spain, prepared with best fresh produce. Caring and loving cooking, make for a delightful meal of earthy cooking, some delicious rices,  the jabugo ham hand cut is superb, and for those who enjoy a good plate of lentilles,  like myself, really delicious slow cooked dishes remind me of my gradmothers potages.The ambiance is elegant and not stuffy, with just the right amount of lively noise of people talking lively. Some days they have live guitar and flamenco short performance, long/short enough to enjoy, and continue enjoying your meal.  If you enjoy a no frils excellent fish or meat with veggies or salad, the cook will do wonders too, personally I have to look after my calories intake, and although my friends can eat everything I also get a delicious and beautiful meal without the guilt. Excelent wines, and you feel free to consult which wine goes better with your dish.The employees go the extra many miles to pamper you, great service. They have a yummy Happy Hour too 😉
